Of the 18 pieces of silverware in the drawer, 6 of them are forks, 6 of them are spoons, and 6 of them are knives. If I reach in and randomly take out 3 pieces of silverware, how can I calculate the probability that I get one fork, one spoon, and one knife? Our initial probability calculation is given by: {eq}\color{blue}{\frac{(f){(s)}{(k)}}{t\choose3}}

{/eq} 

Let {eq}t

{/eq} represent the amount of silverware in the drawer. In this case, {eq}t=18

{/eq}.



Since there are 6 forks in the drawer such as {eq}f=6

{/eq}.



There are 6 spoons in the drawer such that {eq}s=6

{/eq}.



There are 6 knives in the drawer such that {eq}k=6

{/eq}.



The probability that this Student gets one fork, one spoon, and one knife is given by:

{eq}\Large{\color{blue}{\frac{(f)(s)(k)}{t \choose 3}}=\frac{(6)(6)(6)}{18 \choose 3}

\\=\frac{(6)(6)(6)}{\frac{18!}{(18-3)!3!}}

\\=\frac{(6)(6)(6)}{\frac{18!}{(15)!3!}}

\\=\frac{(6)(6)(6)}{\frac{18 \times 17 \times 16}{15 \times 14 \times 13}}

\\=\frac{\frac{216}{3640}}

\\=\color{blue}{\frac{54}{910}}

\\=\color{blue}{\frac{27}{455}}

{/eq}
####
The probability that the User gets one fork, one spoon, and one knife is 27/455.

You have 18 silverware items, 6 forks, 6 spoons, and 6 knives. You randomly remove three silverware items from the drawer.

- Number of ways to choose 1 fork from 6 forks = {6\choose1}
- Number of ways to choose 1 spoon from 6 spoons = {6\choose1}
- Number of ways to choose 1 knife from 6 knives = {6\choose1}
- Number of ways to choose 3 silverware items from 18 silverware items = {18\choose3}

The probability of getting one fork, one spoon, and one knife is given by:

{eq}\frac{{6\choose1 \times 6\choose1} \times {6\choose1}}{{18\choose3}} = \frac{5}{17}

</think>
